: 616, "t": "STEREOTYPED MOVEMENT DISORDER"}, {"i": 617, "t": "F99"}, {"i": 618, "t": "UNSPECIFIED MENTAL DISORDER"}, {"i": 619, "t": "completes"}, {"i": 620, "t": "ICD-10 CODE NOT SPECIFIED"}, {"i": 621, "t": "SYMPTOM DOMAINS OF PRIMARY PSYCHOTIC DISORDERS"}, {"i": 622, "t": "Premenstrual Dysphoric Disorder (PMDD)"}, {"i": 623, "t": "PERSONALITY DIFFICULTY"}, {"i": 624, "t": "OBSTRUCTIVE SLEEP APNEA (OSA)"}, {"i": 625, "t": "narcolepsy"}, {"i": 626, "t": "‹ SCHIZOPHRENIA SPECTRUM"}, {"i": 627, "t": "XBT-11"}, {"i": 628, "t": "6A25"}, {"i": 629, "t": "SYMPTOM DOMAINS OF PRIMARY PSYCHOTIC DISORDERS"}, {"i": 630, "t": "DSM-5-TR"}, {"i": 631, "t": "SYMPTOM DOMAINS OF PRIMARY PSYCHOTIC DISORDERS"}, {"i": 632, "t": "Definition and nosology"}, {"i": 633, "t": "History"}, {"i": 634, "t": "Myths and misconceptions"}, {"i": 635, "t": "Sources"}, {"i": 636, "t": "Six symptom domains"}, {"i": 637, "t": "Clinical use"}, {"i": 638, "t": "Source-specific specifications"}, {"i": 639, "t": "1. Definition and nosology"}, {"i": 640, "t": "6A25"}, {"i": 641, "t": "In ICD-11, the group of primary psychotic disorders (6A20–6A24)"}, {"i": 642, "t": "dimensional alt-strukturu"}, {"i": 643, "t": "dur. Not a separate clinical nosological unit—diagnosis placed as additional qualifier onto primary disorder (e.g., 6A20 Schizophrenia)."}, {"i": 644, "t": "Six symptom domains"}, {"i": 645, "t": "Each is assessed separately for severity level (none / mild / moderate / severe)."}, {"i": 646, "t": "The basis of the concept — to describe the heterogeneous clinical presentation of psychotic disorders using a more valid and dimensional measure instead of classic subtypes (paranoid, hebephrenic, catatonic)."}, {"i": 647, "t": "2. History"}, {"i": 648, "t": "Bleuler's \"4A\" symptoms (1911) and Schneider's \"first-rank symptoms\" (1959) — categorical approach."}, {"i": 649, "t": "Crow T.J. (1980) — Concept of Type I (positive symptom dominant) and Type II (negative dominant) — the basis of the dimensional approach."}, {"i": 650, "t": "Liddle P.F. (1987) — three-dimensional factor — reality distortion, disorganization, psychomotor poverty."}, {"i": 651, "t": "DSM-5 (2013)"}, {"i": 652, "t": "Section III research category proposes dimensional assessment."}, {"i": 653, "t": "XBT-11 (2019)"}, {"i": 654, "t": "6A25"}, {"i": 655, "t": "integrated as an official dimensional qualifier."}, {"i": 656, "t": "3. Myths and misconceptions"}, {"i": 657, "t": "Myth 1: \"6A25 is a separate disorder, can be diagnosed as such\""}, {"i": 658, "t": "Reality:"}, {"i": 659, "t": "6A25 is not a separate clinical entity — it is a qualifier of the primary disorder (6A20–6A24)."}, {"i": 660, "t": "Myth 2: \"Dimensional approach replaces categorical diagnosis\""}, {"i": 661, "t": "Reality:"}, {"i": 662, "t": "both complementary — categorical diagnosis provides nosological unit, dimensional qualifier describes specific clinical presentation."}, {"i": 663, "t": "Myth 3: \"Negative symptoms are side effects of antipsychotics, not 'real'\""}, {"i": 664, "t": "Reality:"}, {"i": 665, "t": "Primary negative symptoms are a core feature of schizophrenia — observed even before antipsychotics. Secondary negative symptoms (sedation, EPS, depression, positive symptom effect) are distinct and manageable."}, {"i": 666, "t": "4. Sources"}, {"i": 667, "t": "WHO. ICD-11. 6A25 Symptomatic manifestations of primary psychotic disorders. 2024."}, {"i": 668, "t": "APA. DSM-5-TR. 2022."}, {"i": 669, "t": "NICE CG178. 2014/2019."}]